{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_0168WQ8mF9jCyMihjindLhow","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to generate 10 realistic fake OCR recipe text files. Let me break down the requirements:\n\n1. Save to `tools/title-loop/input/{RECIPE_TITLE}.generated.21.txt`\n2. FILENAME RULES:\n   - Use SPACES, not hyphens/underscores\n   - Preserve Polish diacritics\n   - Filename title must match main title in content (case-insensitive OK)\n\n3. RECIPE MIX: ~60% English (6), ~40% Polish (4)\n4. Variety of categories: soups, mains, desserts, salads, appetizers, breads, drinks, preserves\n5. Mix of multi-word (2-5 words) and single-word titles\n\n6. MUST BE DIFFERENT from the long list of excluded recipes\n\n7. PATTERN REQUIREMENTS:\n   - 4 files with SPLIT_TITLE (title split across 2-4 lines)\n   - 4 files with NARRATIVE (3-7 lines of prose intro)\n   - 2 files with SIMPLE (basic OCR noise)\n\n8. FILE LENGTH: 15-60 lines (spillover should be 40-60)\n\nLet me plan 10 recipes:\n\nEnglish (6):\n1. Garlic Mushroom Risotto - SPLIT_TITLE\n2. Lentil and Walnut Soup - NARRATIVE\n3. Basil Tomato Pasta - SIMPLE\n4. Blackberry Tart - SPLIT_TITLE\n5. Herb Roasted Chicken Thighs - NARRATIVE\n6. Berry Compote - SIMPLE\n\nPolish (4):\n7. Bigos Wiosenny - NARRATIVE\n8. Kluski Śląskie - SPLIT_TITLE\n9. Żabka w Sosie Pieczarkowym - SPLIT_TITLE\n10. Kompot Czereśniowy - SPLIT_TITLE\n\n\nI need to verify against the exclusion list to ensure none of these overlap with existing recipes. Let me adjust the selections to avoid any duplicates—swapping out similar titles for alternatives like Currant and Berry Compote instead of just Berry Compote, and checking Polish recipes against the provided list to confirm Kluski Śląskie and the others aren't already included. - Polenta Casserole ✓\n\nAll items check out against the exclusion list. My final selection balances six English dishes with four Polish ones, using varied formatting styles across the collection.\n\nNow I'm creating the original content for each recipe. Starting with the English dishes: Garlic Mushroom Risotto uses a split-title format with Arborio rice as the base, building flavor through sautéed garlic, onions, and mushrooms before incorporating the rice and broth. The method involves toasting the rice, then gradually adding warm stock while stirring to achieve that creamy consistency, finished with Parmesan and fresh herbs.\n\nThe Lentil Walnut Soup takes a narrative approach, emphasizing how the earthy legumes pair with nutty walnuts to create a satisfying, protein-packed dish. It's naturally plant-based and traditionally paired with crusty bread and walnut oil for depth.\n\nThe ingredient list includes lentils, walnuts, aromatics, vegetable broth, olive oil, cumin, smoked paprika, and fresh thyme. The preparation involves sautéing the onion, carrots, celery, and garlic, then adding the lentils, walnuts, and spices before simmering in broth for about 40 minutes until the lentils soften completely. Season to taste and serve hot.\n\nFor the tomato basil pasta, I need to sauté minced garlic and diced onion in olive oil until fragrant, then add the tomatoes and let them break down over 20-25 minutes while seasoning with salt, pepper, and a touch of sugar. Cook the pasta separately to al dente, reserving some pasta water to adjust the sauce consistency, then combine everything with fresh basil and finish with Parmesan cheese.\n\nNow for the blackberry tart—the crust comes together by cutting cold butter into a flour and powdered sugar mixture until it resembles breadcrumbs, then binding it with an egg yolk mixed with ice water. After chilling the dough for 30 minutes, I'll roll it out and fill it with fresh blackberries tossed with sugar, cornstarch, lemon juice, and vanilla extract.\n\nFor the herb roasted chicken thighs, this is a straightforward approach that highlights how the natural juices stay locked in during cooking. The aromatic herbs create a flavorful exterior while keeping the meat tender inside, making it approachable for someone learning to roast poultry. Pairing it with roasted vegetables rounds out the meal nicely.\n\nThe method involves preheating to 425°F, positioning the thighs skin-side up, coating them with oil and seasonings, then scattering fresh thyme, rosemary, bay leaves, garlic, and lemon throughout the pan. Chicken broth goes around the base rather than over top. The thighs roast for 40-45 minutes until the skin turns golden and the internal temperature hits 165°F, then rest before serving.\n\nFor the compote, combine red currants, blackberries, and raspberries with sugar and water in a heavy pot. Bring to a gentle boil over medium heat while stirring to dissolve the sugar, then add lemon juice and a split vanilla pod. Let it simmer for 45-60 minutes, skimming off foam as it rises. The compote finishes when it passes the wrinkle test. kg młodej kapusty, 500g wieprzowiny, 300g grzybów, marchewkę, cebulę i pastę pomidorową. Sezonuję majerankiem, liśćmi laurowymi, solą i pieprzem, a następnie dodaję rosół. Mięso przesmażam na oleju, dorzucam warzywa i grzyby, pozwalam wszystkiemu dusić się razem do miękkości.\n\nCałość gotuje się na małym ogniu przez 45 minut, aż składniki się połączą. Podaję gorące.\n\nDo kluskiśląskich: ziemniaki obierz i gotuj do miękkości, następnie przełóż przez praskę. Wymieszaj z mąką, jajami, posiekaną cebulą, solą i pieprzem, formując kulki. Na nadzienie smaż bekon z cebulą i mięsem mielonym, wciśnij to do każdej kulki i gotuj w osolonej wodzie aż wypłyną na powierzchnię. Podawaj z bigos lub żurem.\n\nZupa koperkowa wymaga rozpuszczenia masła w garnku, dodania mąki na roux, a następnie powolnego wlewania mleka przy stałym mieszaniu. Dodaj pokrojone warzywa (marchewkę, cebulę, ziemniaki) i gotuj około 20 minut, aż będą miękkie. Na koniec wsyp świeży koperek i jeśli chcesz, roztrzep jaja, dodając je powoli do gorącej zupy. Dopraw solą i pieprzem, podawaj gorącą z garnirą z kopru.\n\nKompot czereśniowy wymaga przygotowania czereśni poprzez usunięcie pestek. Składniki to czereśnie, woda, cukier, sok z cytryn oraz przyprawy takie jak kardamon, cynamon i goździki.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":64866,"cache_read_input_tokens":15568,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":64866},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c22f6373-1768-4fe9-8dfb-d92d5ab5fdd9","uuid":"b8ab6620-3794-487a-b59c-c87444f3e047"}
